  <span id="freeText10351797743197000814" style="display:none">Amidst all the crisis that are taking place in the world, slave trade continues to havoc in parts of Africa, with children getting abducted in large numbers. Sometimes these incidents make it to the news but most of the time they go unreported. [The most recent news report is from Libya where the auction was held in open, much to horror of the world.]<br /><br />Mende Nazer managed to escape a rich Arab family and sought asylum in Britain. This book is her memoir as she recounts the events leading up to her enslavement and the torture that began after. Even in her darkest moments, Mende Nazer exhibited kindness to those around her. She perseveres quietly till her eventual freedom. The village she lived in was pillaged, men murdered, women raped and the children were first raped and then sold into slavery. The bigger tragedy here is that the families who buy these slaves are well respected in the society and the family to which she was sent to, worked in embassy. <br /><br />I am close to Nazer's age and thus her narration had a personal greater impact. When she talks about her mistress and the cruel emotional abuse she imposes on Nazer, I look back at my own life and remember what I was doing at that time. This put the experiences she goes through as a child in perspective to how the world and my life was changing. If/When you read this book, the things that are done to her makes you look away.<br /><br />Don't look away.</span>
